<BLOCK1><TI>CLAIM</TI>
<P>1. The plaintiffs claim:
<P1>a) General damages in an amount to be determined by this Honourable Court;</P1>
<P1>b) Special damages in an amount not yet ascertained and to be established at trial;</P1>
<P1>c) Punitive, aggravated and exemplary damages in an amount to be determined by this Honourable Court;</P1>
<P1>d) Interest in accordance with the Queen's Bench Act;</P1>
<P1>e) Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
<P>2. The plaintiff Patrick Guilbert (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;Guilbert&rdquo;) is a resident of the Town of Neepawa, in the Province of Manitoba, and at all times material hereto, is and was an entrepreneur; the plaintiff Guilbert Enterprises Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;Enterprises&rdquo;) was a company, the shares of which were owned by the plaintiff Guilbert, and was a Manitoba company.</P>
<P>3. The defendant is an insurance company registered as such in the Province of Manitoba to carry on business and is incorporated pursuant to the laws of Canada. Its head office is in Waterloo, in the Province of Ontario.</P>
<P>4. The plaintiffs state that they operated a business operated as Neepawa Home Hardware in the Town of Neepawa, in Manitoba.</P>
<P>5. The plaintiffs state that they had a commercial insurance policy with the defendant under Policy No. 9385038.</P>
<P>6. The plaintiffs state further, that on or about 6: 00 p.m. on February 25, 2015, the store known as Neepawa Home Hardware, at XXXXXXXXXX, burned to the ground. The plaintiffs state further that above the main level of the building owned by the plaintiff Enterprises, were condo residences that had been built by the plaintiffs and were occupied at the time of the fire.</P>
<P>7. The plaintiffs state that the fire was accidental and that the Fire Commissioner of Manitoba, investigated said fire and concluded in its report that &ldquo;there is no possibility, nor was there the opportunity for human action to have caused this fire in the identified area of origin. The only source of ignition in this area is electrical wiring&rdquo;.</P>
<P>8. The plaintiffs state that the conclusions of the Fire Commissioner were at all times material known to the defendant.</P>
<P>9. The plaintiffs state that Enterprises submitted a Proof of Loss in final form to the defendant on June 17, 2015.</P>
<P>10. The plaintiffs state that by correspondence from counsel for the defendant to counsel for the plaintiffs, the defendant denied liability and alleged that the plaintiff Guilbert deliberately and criminally set the fire which caused the loss in question.</P>
<P>11. The plaintiffs state that the policy of insurance with the defendant was a replacement cost policy and that the amount of insurance loss claimed and the proof of loss was, for building equipment and fixtures and furniture, a total of $3,022,593.80, particulars of which will be provided at the trial.</P>
<P>12. The plaintiffs state that the defendant has refused without justification to cover the said loss which refusal was a breach of the policy of insurance between the defendant and the plaintiff Enterprises. The plaintiffs state that the defendant, taking the position as it has that the fire loss was caused by the criminal act of the plaintiff Guilbert, is false and egregious; the plaintiff Guilbert states further, that at all times material hereto, the defendant knew that the plaintiff Guilbert was the operating mind of the plaintiff Enterprises.</P>
<P>13. The plaintiffs state that the allegation by the defendant of the criminal act of arson, has been made by the defendant falsely and maliciously and designed to provide it an economic benefit. It has caused the plaintiff Guilbert emotional distress, angst and reputational damage and is a breach of the duty of good faith and a breach of contract (as between the defendant and plaintiff Enterprises).</P>
<P>14. The plaintiff states that the defendant has maintained its position that the plaintiffs were involved in a criminal offence vitiating the insurance policy in the face of a Fire Commissioner's report exonerating the plaintiffs and declaring that the fire was innocently set and did so falsely, egregiously, and in a reckless and highhanded manner, and therefore, the defendant should be liable to pay punitive, exemplary and aggravated damages.</P>
